              }
            ],
            "defaultServings": 4
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "attrs": {
            "level": 2
          },
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Method",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "attrs": {
            "level": 3
          },
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Make the herb crust",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "orderedList",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Heat the oven to 220 degrees C fan. In a food processor or by hand, blitz the breadcrumbs, parsley, rosemary, garlic, and olive oil until a coarse, bright green paste forms.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Season the racks with salt and pepper. Brush the meaty side of each rack with Dijon mustard, then press the herb crust firmly on top in an even layer.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "attrs": {
            "level": 3
          },
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Roast and rest",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "orderedList",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Place the racks crust-side up in a roasting tin, with the bones pointing upward. The ",
                      "type": "text"
                    },
                    {
                      "text": "French-trimmed",
                      "type": "text",
                      "marks": [
                        {
                          "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                          "attrs": {
                            "termId": "cmpsohvyq0000awv4c507n8xs"
                          }
                        }
                      ]
                    },
                    {
                      "text": " bones protect the meat and allow air to circulate. Roast for 22 to 25 minutes for medium-rare (internal temperature 58 to 60 degrees C).",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Transfer to a warm board and ",
                      "type": "text"
                    },
                    {
                      "text": "rest",
                      "type": "text",
                      "marks": [
                        {
                          "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                          "attrs": {
                            "termId": "cmpedfvv30001x4v4rzqb2aze"
                          }
                        }
                      ]
                    },
                    {
                      "text": " for 10 minutes. Carve between the ribs into individual cutlets to serve.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "troubleshooter",
          "attrs": {
            "items": [
              {
                "fix": "Apply the mustard to a completely cold rack. The crust adheres best to cold meat. Press it on firmly with your hands.",
                "cause": "The mustard was applied to a warm surface so it did not set, or the crust was too dry.",
                "symptom": "The crust is falling off during carving"
              },
              {
                "fix": "Use a thermometer to check doneness. A thermapen reads instantly. Aim for 58 degrees C in the thickest part of the meat, not the bone.",
                "cause": "The oven was too hot or the racks were small.",
                "symptom": "The crust is golden but the meat is overcooked"
              },
              {
                "fix": "Always allow the meat to come to room temperature for 30 minutes. A well-preheated oven at 220 degrees C should colour the crust in the first 10 minutes.",
                "cause": "The oven was not properly preheated, or the racks were refrigerator-cold when they went in.",
                "symptom": "The crust is pale and soft after roasting"
              },
              {
                "fix": "Lean the racks against each other in the tin so the bones interlock. This keeps them upright and allows them to cook more evenly.",
                "cause": "Uneven rack sizes, or one was positioned differently in the oven.",
                "symptom": "One rack is done before the other"
              }
            ]
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "attrs": {
            "level": 2
          },
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Variations",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Replace the herb crust with a pistachio and mint version: blitz shelled pistachios, fresh mint, and olive oil instead of breadcrumbs and rosemary. For a simpler finish, skip the crust entirely and just season well with salt and a rub of rosemary oil.",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "attrs": {
            "level": 2
          },
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Where this dish lives",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Rack of lamb is a French technique adopted into British fine dining and then into domestic cooking by the 1980s. The French trimming of the bones is purely aesthetic, but has become the expected presentation. It is the standard Easter centrepiece in households that want something more elegant than a leg, and faster than a shoulder.",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    "servings": 4,
    "yieldDescription": null,
    "difficulty": "INTERMEDIATE"
  },
